"Bowerman N.H.A., Frame D.J., Huntingford C., Lowe J.A., Allen M.R.","Cumulative carbon emissions, emissions floors and short-term rates of warming: Implications for policy",2011,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society A: Mathematical, Physical and Engineering Sciences","369","1934",,"45","66",,,10.1098/rsta.2010.0288,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79251469765&partnerID=40&md5=8feeabea2f997124f58ee95dc24049a2","Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics, Department of Physics, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3PU, United Kingdom; Smith School of Enterprise and the Environment, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 2BQ, United Kingdom; Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Department of Meteorology, Met Office Hadley Centre (Reading Unit), University of Reading, Reading RG6 6BB, United Kingdom","Bowerman, N.H.A., Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics, Department of Physics, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3PU, United Kingdom; Frame, D.J., Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics, Department of Physics, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3PU, United Kingdom, Smith School of Enterprise and the Environment, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 2BQ, United Kingdom; Huntingford, C., Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Lowe, J.A., Department of Meteorology, Met Office Hadley Centre (Reading Unit), University of Reading, Reading RG6 6BB, United Kingdom; Allen, M.R., Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics, Department of Physics, University of Oxford, Oxford OX1 3PU, United Kingdom","A number of recent studies have found a strong link between peak human-induced global warming and cumulative carbon emissions from the start of the industrial revolution while the link to emissions over shorter periods or in the years 2020 or 2050 is generally weaker. However cumulative targets appear to conflict with the concept of a 'floor' in emissions caused by sectors such as food production. Here we show that the introduction of emissions floors does not reduce the importance of cumulative emissions but may make some warming targets unachievable. For pathways that give a most likely warming up to about 4° C cumulative emissions from pre-industrial times to year 2200 correlate strongly with most likely resultant peak warming regardless of the shape of emissions floors used providing a more natural long-term policy horizon than 2050 or 2100. The maximum rate of CO 2-induced warming which will affect the feasibility and cost of adapting to climate change is not determined by cumulative emissions but is tightly aligned with peak rates of emissions. Hence cumulative carbon emissions to 2200 and peak emission rates could provide a clear and simple framework for CO 2 mitigation policy. ©2011 The Royal Society.","Climate change; Cumulative emissions; Emissions floors; Rate of warming","Carbon emissions; Cumulative emissions; Emissions floors; Food production; Industrial revolutions; Long-term policies; Mitigation policies; Peak emissions; Pre-industrial; Rate of warming; Strong link; Floors; Global warming; Industrial emissions",,,,,,"Archer, D., Fate of fossil fuel CO 2 in geologic time (2005) Journal of Geophysical Research C: Oceans, 110 (9), pp. 1-6. , DOI 10.1029/2004JC002625, C09S05; Solomon, S., Plattner, G.K., Knutti, R., Friedlingstein, P., Irreversible climate change due to carbon dioxide emissions (2009) Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA, 106, pp. 1704-1709. , doi:10.1073/ pnas.0812721106; Cox, P.M., Betts, R.A., Jones, C.D., Spall, S.A., Totterdell, I.J., Acceleration of global warming due to carbon-cycle feedbacks in a coupled climate model (2000) Nature, 408, pp. 184-187. , doi:10.1038/35041539; Friedlingstein, P., Cox, P., Betts, R., Bopp, L., Von Bloh, W., Brovkin, V., Cadule, P., Zeng, N., Climate-carbon cycle feedback analysis: Results from the C 4MIP model intercomparison (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (14), pp. 3337-3353. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3800.1; P